⚙️ Automation Logic
Automated Employee Onboarding & Offboarding System

Automation Logic defines how the system reacts to events, triggers workflows, executes tasks, and enforces rules automatically across HR, IT, IAM, and compliance layers.

1. Core Concept

The system is event-driven + rule-based automation:

Event → Rule Engine → Workflow → Actions → Audit Log

Example:

New employee added → triggers onboarding workflow → creates accounts → assigns roles → logs everything
2. Types of Automation
2.1 Event-Based Automation

Triggered by system events:

NEW_HIRE
EXIT_APPROVED
ROLE_CHANGED
DOCUMENT_SIGNED
2.2 Rule-Based Automation

Triggered by conditions:

Example rules:

If department = "Engineering" → assign GitHub + Dev tools
If role = Manager → grant approval permissions
If exit_date is set → trigger offboarding
2.3 Time-Based Automation

Triggered by schedules:

Send onboarding reminders daily
Auto-disable inactive accounts after 30 days
Archive exited employees after retention period
3. Automation Engine Core (Code)
3.1 Event Dispatcher
class EventDispatcher:

    def __init__(self, workflow_engine):
        self.workflow_engine = workflow_engine

    def dispatch(self, event_type, payload):
        if event_type == "NEW_HIRE":
            self.workflow_engine.start_onboarding(payload)

        elif event_type == "EXIT_APPROVED":
            self.workflow_engine.start_offboarding(payload)

        elif event_type == "ROLE_CHANGED":
            self.workflow_engine.update_access(payload)

        else:
            raise Exception("Unknown event type")
4. Workflow Automation Engine
class WorkflowEngine:

    def start_onboarding(self, employee):
        self.create_account(employee)
        self.assign_roles(employee)
        self.trigger_tasks(employee)
        self.log("ONBOARDING_STARTED", employee["id"])

    def start_offboarding(self, employee):
        self.revoke_access(employee["id"])
        self.archive_data(employee["id"])
        self.log("OFFBOARDING_COMPLETED", employee["id"])

    def update_access(self, payload):
        self.sync_roles(payload["employee_id"], payload["new_role"])
        self.log("ROLE_UPDATED", payload["employee_id"])
5. Rule Engine (Business Logic Automation)
5.1 Rule Definition
rules = [
    {
        "condition": lambda e: e["department"] == "Engineering",
        "action": "grant_dev_tools"
    },
    {
        "condition": lambda e: e["role"] == "Manager",
        "action": "enable_approval_rights"
    }
]
5.2 Rule Processor
class RuleEngine:

    def apply_rules(self, employee):
        for rule in rules:
            if rule["condition"](employee):
                self.execute(rule["action"], employee)

    def execute(self, action, employee):
        if action == "grant_dev_tools":
            print(f"Granting dev tools to {employee['id']}")

        elif action == "enable_approval_rights":
            print(f"Enabling approvals for {employee['id']}")
